**THE DALLAS HERALD**

  ----------------------- ----------------------- -----------------------
  *Dallas, Texas*         **Thursday, March 22,   *Five Cents*
                          1910**                  

  ----------------------- ----------------------- -----------------------

**HARTLEY DEATH RULED SUICIDE**

*Prominent Businessman Found Dead; Investigation*

*Concludes Self-Inflicted Wound*

***By James P. Mitchell, Staff Writer***

Robert Hartley, 52, co-founder of the highly successful Thoreson &
Hartley Toys manufacturing concern, was found dead in his study on the
evening of March 15th. Investigators have ruled his death a suicide.

Police were called to the residence on Swiss Avenue at approximately 7
p.m. following a report from household staff. Mr. Hartley was discovered
with a fatal gunshot wound to the head. A revolver was found at the
scene.

Inspector William Clark of the Dallas Police Department stated that
evidence at the scene is consistent with self-infliction. "There are no
signs of struggle, no indication of forced entry, and the positioning of
the weapon suggests Mr. Hartley acted alone," the inspector reported.

The circumstances preceding his death remain unclear. However, sources
close to the family indicate that Mr. Hartley had been under
considerable business strain in recent weeks. Of particular note: a
document transferring sole ownership of Thoreson & Hartley Toys to
William Thoreson was executed just one day prior to Mr. Hartley's death.

This transfer prompted initial inquiries by investigators, and Mr.
Thoreson was questioned extensively regarding the circumstances of the
document's execution and Mr. Hartley's state of mind. However, after
thorough examination of the evidence and witness statements, police have
concluded that Mr. Hartley's death was indeed self-inflicted, and that
Mr. Thoreson bears no responsibility for the tragedy.

*"Robert and I had our differences of late," Mr. Thoreson stated to this
paper, "but I cannot fathom what drove him to such a desperate act. It
is a tragedy of the deepest magnitude."*

Funeral services are scheduled for Saturday at 2 p.m. at First
Presbyterian Church.

